  number    = {9},
  pages     = {1979 - 97},
  volume    = {44},
  abstract  = {A numerical study of neutral beam injection into spheromaks is presented.
	The beam evolution is calculated through a Monte-Carlo simulation
	and the plasma MHD equilibrium is determined self-consistently with
	the current produced by the beam. The exact equations of motion are
	used for the beam particles instead of the usual guiding-centre approximation.
	The guiding-centre trajectories are clearly different from the actual
	particle trajectories and this difference produces discrepancies
	in the total driven current and in the current profiles. A reduction
	of the plasma effective charge, Z<sub>eff</sub>, does not result
	in an improvement in the current drive efficiency because the reduction
	of the stopping cross section is compensated by an increase in the
	electron cancelling current. The safety factor profile of the self-consistent
	equilibria shows a clear sensitivity to the driven current profile.
