	surface, where both the plasma and the neutral density are higher
	than in the bulk plasma and where intense ionization occurs. The
	ions formed in this layer fall back onto the cathode, whereas electrons
	contribute to the high current density in the bulk plasma. The particle
	balance in the ionizing layer is determined by the recycling coefficient,
	which, in turn, depends on the cathode temperature and the sheath
	voltage. As it turns out, these dependences give rise to an instability
