	(and the hot spots), which are in a general agreement with discoloration
	patterns on the surface of the cathode in the SSPX. If the magnetic
	field is tilted to the surface, the footpoints of the filaments move
	with a significant velocity, whose direction depends on the ratio
	of the ion gyroradius and the thickness of the ionizing layer. This
	instability, although primarily considered in conjunction with the
	SSPX experiment, may play a role in spherical tokamaks and other
	systems with coaxial helicity injection},
