  year      = {2000/03/},
  issn      = {1070-664X},
  note      = {internal kink mode;tokamak;toroidal plasma rotation;stability;large aspect ratio expansion;compressible magnetohydrodynamic equations;central poloidal beta;rotational frequencies;Alfven frequency;inverse aspect ratio;Doppler-shifted frequency;adiabatic index;sonic Mach number;centrifugal force;magnetic surface;Brunt-Vaisala oscillations;stably stratified fluid;gravitational field;internal kink instability;kinetic behavior;},
  number    = {3},
  pages     = {923 - 30},
  volume    = {7},
  abstract  = {The stability of the internal m=n=1 kink mode is analyzed for a tokamak
	with a toroidally rotating plasma, by a large aspect ratio expansion
	of the compressible magnetohydrodynamic equations. Assuming that
	the central poloidal beta is of order unity, it is found that the
	internal kink mode is stabilized by rotational frequencies of order
	&Omega;/&omega;<sub>A</sub>~&epsiv;, where &omega;<sub>A</sub> is
	the Alfv&eacute;n frequency and &epsiv; is the inverse aspect ratio.
	The internal kink then turns into a stable oscillation with a Doppler-shifted
	frequency ~&Omega;M(1-1/&Gamma;)<sup>1/2</sup>, where &Gamma; is
	the adiabatic index and M is the sonic Mach number. The stabilization
	comes from the centrifugal force which gives a stable density (or
	entropy) distribution within each magnetic surface. The parallel
	motion associated with the internal kink mode then behaves as the
	Brunt-V&auml;is&auml;l&auml; oscillations of a stably stratified
	fluid in a gravitational field. At lower rotational frequencies,
	&Omega;/&omega;<sub>A</sub>~&epsiv;<sup>2</sup>, the only effect
